{
  "What produces magnetic fields?": "",
  "Moving charges (currents) and permanent magnets": "",
  "Stationary electric charges and neutral conductors": "",
  "Longitudinal sound waves traveling through metals": "",
  "Gravitational attraction between massive bodies": "",
  "Magnetic fields are produced by moving charges (currents) and permanent magnets.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of magnetic field?": "",
  "Weber (Wb)": "",
  "Newton (N)": "",
  "Tesla (T)": "",
  "Henry (H)": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic field strength is the Tesla (T).": "",
  "Does a stationary charge experience a magnetic force?": "",
  "Yes, always": "",
  "No, never": "",
  "In strong fields": "",
  "Near magnets": "",
  "A stationary charge does not experience a magnetic force. The charge must be moving (F = qvB sin θ).": "",
  "What is the force on a moving charge in a B field?": "",
  "F = qvB cos θ": "",
  "F = qv/B": "",
  "F = qvB sin θ": "",
  "F = qB/v": "",
  "F = qvB sin θ, where θ is the angle between v and B.": "",
  "Does the magnetic force do work on a moving charge?": "",
  "Yes": "",
  "Only at high speeds": "",
  "No — it changes direction only": "",
  "Only for electrons": "",
  "The magnetic force is always perpendicular to velocity, so it does no work — it only changes the direction of motion, not the speed.": "",
  "The magnetic force is perpendicular to:": "",
  "Neither": "",
  "Both v and B": "",
  "Only v": "",
  "Only B": "",
  "F = qv × B. The cross product gives a force perpendicular to both v and B.": "",
  "Magnetic field lines outside a magnet go from:": "",
  "They don't have direction": "",
  "East to West": "",
  "South to North": "",
  "North to South": "",
  "Outside a magnet, field lines go from the north pole to the south pole. Inside the magnet, they go south to north, forming closed loops.": "",
  "What rule determines the direction of the magnetic force on a positive charge?": "",
  "The left-hand rule for positive charges": "",
  "The right-hand rule for positive charges": "",
  "The principle of superposition for forces": "",
  "Lenz's Law for induced current direction": "",
  "The right-hand rule: point fingers in the direction of velocity, curl them toward B, and the thumb points in the direction of the force on a positive charge.": "",
  "What is the force on a current-carrying wire in a magnetic field?": "",
  "F = BIL sin θ": "",
  "F = BIL cos θ": "",
  "F = BI/L sin θ": "",
  "F = B/(IL) sin θ": "",
  "F = BIL sin θ, where B is field strength, I is current, L is wire length, and θ is the angle between the wire and field.": "",
  "What path does a charged particle follow in a uniform magnetic field?": "",
  "A straight line path in the field direction": "",
  "A circular or helical path perpendicular to B": "",
  "A parabolic path like a projectile in gravity": "",
  "An elliptical path around the field source": "",
  "The magnetic force is always perpendicular to velocity, acting as a centripetal force. This causes the particle to move in a circular (or helical if there is a velocity component along B) path.": "",
  "What is a 'magnetic field'?": "",
  "A region where a moving charge or magnetic material experiences a force": "",
  "A region where stationary electric charges experience a repulsive force": "",
  "A field created only by permanent magnets and not by electric currents": "",
  "The force between two gravitationally attracted massive objects in space": "",
  "A magnetic field is a region of space where moving charges and magnetic materials experience a force. It is produced by moving charges and permanent magnets.": "",
  "What does the 'Tesla' (T) measure?": "",
  "The strength of an electric field in volts per meter": "",
  "The strength of a magnetic field in a region of space": "",
  "The total magnetic flux through a closed surface area": "",
  "The inductance of a coil measured in henries per meter": "",
  "The Tesla (T) is the SI unit of magnetic field strength. 1 T = 1 kg/(A·s²). The Earth's magnetic field is about 5 × 10⁻⁵ T.": "",
  "What is the 'right-hand rule' in magnetism?": "",
  "A rule for determining the direction of force on a positive moving charge in a field": "",
  "A rule that states magnetic force is always directed toward the right side": "",
  "A rule for calculating the magnitude of the magnetic force on a charge": "",
  "A rule that only applies to permanent magnets and not to electromagnets": "",
  "The right-hand rule determines the direction of the magnetic force: point fingers along v, curl toward B, and the thumb gives the force direction on a positive charge.": "",
  "What is a 'magnetic field line'?": "",
  "A physical wire that creates a magnetic field when current passes through": "",
  "An imaginary line showing the direction a north pole would move in the field": "",
  "The boundary between a magnetic north region and south region in space": "",
  "A line along which the magnetic force has its maximum possible magnitude": "",
  "Magnetic field lines are imaginary lines that show the direction of the magnetic field at every point. A compass needle (north pole) aligns along these lines.": "",
  "What is a 'solenoid'?": "",
  "A single straight wire carrying a large electrical current through a circuit": "",
  "A coil of wire that produces a uniform magnetic field inside when current flows": "",
  "A permanent magnet shaped like a horseshoe for attracting iron objects": "",
  "A device that measures the strength of a magnetic field at a point": "",
  "A solenoid is a tightly wound coil of wire. When current flows through it, it produces a nearly uniform magnetic field inside, similar to a bar magnet.": "",
  "What is an 'electromagnet'?": "",
  "A permanent magnet that never loses its magnetic field strength over time": "",
  "A magnet created by running electric current through a coil of wire": "",
  "A natural mineral that has inherent magnetic properties from formation": "",
  "A device that converts magnetic energy directly into electrical energy": "",
  "An electromagnet is a magnet produced by electric current flowing through a coil. Its strength can be controlled by changing the current, and it can be turned on and off.": "",
  "What does 'Lorentz force' refer to?": "",
  "The total force on a charged particle from both electric and magnetic fields": "",
  "The gravitational force acting on a charged particle near a massive body": "",
  "The force between two permanent magnets placed near each other in space": "",
  "The friction force that opposes the motion of charges in a conductor wire": "",
  "The Lorentz force is the total electromagnetic force on a charged particle: F = qE + qv × B. It combines both the electric force and the magnetic force.": "",
  "What does 'ferromagnetic' mean?": "",
  "A material that is repelled by all magnetic fields under every condition": "",
  "A material that can be strongly magnetized, like iron, nickel, or cobalt": "",
  "A material that is completely unaffected by any magnetic field at all": "",
  "A material that conducts electricity but cannot be magnetized in any way": "",
  "Ferromagnetic materials (iron, nickel, cobalt) can be strongly magnetized. Their atomic magnetic domains can align, creating a strong net magnetic field.": "",
  "What is 'magnetic flux density'?": "",
  "Another name for the magnetic field strength B measured in teslas": "",
  "The total magnetic flux passing through a surface measured in webers": "",
  "The number of magnetic field lines drawn in a diagram per unit length": "",
  "The rate of change of magnetic flux that induces an electromotive force": "",
  "Magnetic flux density (B) is another term for the magnetic field strength, measured in teslas (T). It represents the amount of magnetic flux per unit area.": "",
  "What are 'magnetic poles'?": "",
  "The regions at each end of a magnet where the magnetic field is strongest": "",
  "The center of a magnet where the magnetic field is at its maximum value": "",
  "Points in space where the magnetic field is exactly equal to zero always": "",
  "The electric charges that create the magnetic field around a wire conductor": "",
  "Magnetic poles are the two ends of a magnet (north and south) where the magnetic field is strongest. Like poles repel; unlike poles attract. Magnetic monopoles have never been observed.": "",
  "A student moves a positive charge to the right in a magnetic field pointing into the page. Using the right-hand rule, which direction is the force?": "",
  "The force on the charge is directed to the right": "",
  "The force on the charge is directed downward": "",
  "The force on the charge is directed upward": "",
  "The force on the charge is directed to the left": "",
  "Right-hand rule: fingers point right (v), curl into the page (B), thumb points upward. The force on the positive charge is upward.": "",
  "A student places a compass near a straight wire carrying current upward. Which way does the compass needle point?": "",
  "The needle points in the same direction as the current (upward)": "",
  "The needle aligns tangent to a circle around the wire per the right-hand rule": "",
  "The needle points directly toward the wire from any position near it": "",
  "The needle spins randomly because wires do not create magnetic fields": "",
  "A current-carrying wire creates circular magnetic field lines around it. Using the right-hand rule (thumb along current, fingers curl in the field direction), the compass needle aligns tangent to these circles.": "",
  "A student shoots an electron straight into a uniform magnetic field. The electron curves into a circle. Why doesn't the electron speed up or slow down?": "",
  "The magnetic field is too weak to change the electron's speed at all": "",
  "The magnetic force is always perpendicular to velocity so it does no work": "",
  "The electron has too much mass for the magnetic force to accelerate it": "",
  "The electric field inside the magnet cancels out the magnetic acceleration": "",
  "The magnetic force F = qv × B is always perpendicular to the velocity, so it can only change the direction of motion, not the speed. No work is done, so kinetic energy (and speed) remain constant.": "",
  "In a lab, a student passes current through a wire placed between two magnets. The wire jumps sideways. What principle explains this?": "",
  "Electromagnetic induction generates a voltage that repels the nearby magnets": "",
  "A current-carrying wire in a magnetic field experiences a force (F = BIL)": "",
  "The wire becomes magnetized and repels both of the magnets equally": "",
  "Thermal expansion from the current causes the wire to bend sideways": "",
  "A current-carrying wire in an external magnetic field experiences a force F = BIL sin θ. This is the motor effect and is the principle behind electric motors.": "",
  "A student increases the current in a solenoid. What happens to the magnetic field inside?": "",
  "The magnetic field inside the solenoid decreases in strength": "",
  "The magnetic field inside the solenoid increases in strength": "",
  "The magnetic field stays exactly the same regardless of current": "",
  "The magnetic field reverses direction inside the solenoid coil": "",
  "The magnetic field inside a solenoid is B = μ₀nI, directly proportional to current I. Increasing current increases the field strength.": "",
  "A student wraps an iron nail with wire and connects it to a battery. The nail picks up paper clips. When the battery is disconnected, the clips fall. Why?": "",
  "The nail was permanently magnetized but the battery absorbed the magnetism": "",
  "The nail was a temporary electromagnet that loses its field without current": "",
  "The paper clips became too heavy for the nail to hold without power": "",
  "The wire melted from the battery heat and released the paper clips": "",
  "The current-carrying coil around the iron nail created an electromagnet. Iron is a soft magnetic material that loses most of its magnetism when the current stops, so the clips fall off.": "",
  "A student learns that electric motors use the force on a current-carrying coil in a magnetic field. What converts the electrical energy?": "",
  "The battery converts electrical energy into kinetic energy of rotation": "",
  "The magnetic force on the current-carrying coil converts it into rotation": "",
  "Friction between the coil and magnets generates the rotational motion": "",
  "Heat from the current causes expansion that pushes the coil around": "",
  "In a motor, current flows through a coil placed in a magnetic field. The force F = BIL on each side of the coil creates a torque that causes rotation, converting electrical energy to mechanical energy.": "",
  "A student moves a charge parallel to a magnetic field. What magnetic force does it experience?": "",
  "Maximum force because the charge is aligned with the field direction": "",
  "Zero force because sin(0°) = 0 in the force equation F = qvB sin θ": "",
  "Half the maximum force because the angle is between 0° and 90°": "",
  "Infinite force because parallel motion maximizes the cross product": "",
  "F = qvB sin θ. When the charge moves parallel to B, θ = 0° and sin(0°) = 0, so F = 0. The charge must have a velocity component perpendicular to B to experience a magnetic force.": "",
  "A student uses a magnetic field to separate charged particles by mass in a mass spectrometer. How does this work?": "",
  "Heavier particles are attracted more strongly to the magnetic field source": "",
  "Different masses curve in different radius circles because r = mv/(qB)": "",
  "The magnetic field slows down heavier particles more than lighter ones": "",
  "Lighter particles are absorbed by the magnetic field while heavier pass through": "",
  "In a mass spectrometer, charged particles enter a magnetic field and curve. The radius of curvature r = mv/(qB) depends on mass. Heavier particles follow larger circles, allowing separation by mass.": "",
  "A student places two parallel wires carrying current in the same direction near each other. What happens?": "",
  "The wires repel each other and move apart from one another": "",
  "The wires attract each other and move closer together": "",
  "Nothing happens because wires do not interact magnetically at all": "",
  "The wires twist around each other into a spiral shape formation": "",
  "Parallel currents in the same direction attract each other. Each wire's magnetic field exerts a force on the other wire's current, pulling them together. Opposite currents repel.": ""
}